  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Milan who spent much of her life in education and community work, I’ve observed how stereotype threat can quietly undermine talented individuals in STEM fields. Stereotype threat refers to the anxiety people feel when they fear their actions might confirm negative stereotypes about their group. For instance, a girl in a physics class might worry that her questions will prove she’s 'not good at math,' which can lead to decreased performance and disengagement. This phenomenon isn’t just theoretical—it’s real and deeply felt by many. In my community, I’ve seen it play out in local schools where students from minority backgrounds or those who don’t fit traditional gender norms hesitate to participate in science discussions. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the approach must be thoughtful and inclusive. Instead of labeling students as 'stereotyped,' we should foster environments where everyone feels safe to explore without fear of judgment. For example, encouraging collaborative problem-solving over competitive exams can reduce anxiety. I’ve also noticed that simple gestures, like acknowledging diverse backgrounds and sharing stories of scientists from underrepresented groups, help build confidence. My anxiety as a retired person sometimes makes me overthink these issues, but I believe addressing stereotype threat is crucial for creating a more equitable future. It’s not about fixing people—it’s about changing the system to support all learners. After all, in my life, I’ve seen how small, consistent efforts can lead to big changes, especially when we listen and adapt to those who feel marginalized.",
